A perfect number is a positive integer that is equal to the sum of its proper divisors, excluding itself. In other words, the sum of all its divisors, other than the number itself, is equal to the number.
• 6 is a perfect number because its divisors (excluding itself) are 1, 2, and 3, and 1+2+3=61 + 2 + 3 = 61+2+3=6.
• 28 is a perfect number because its divisors (excluding itself) are 1, 2, 4, 7, and 14, and 1+2+4+7+14=281 + 2 + 4 + 7 + 14 = 281+2+4+7+14=28.
Perfect numbers are relatively rare, and the next perfect number after 8128 is 33,550,336.
